<subSubSection pageId="82" pageNumber="82" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageId="82" pageNumber="82">
3. 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:138738" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Drepanognathus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Drepanognathus venator Smith" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="82" pageNumber="82" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="venator">Drepanognathus venator</taxonomicName>
. B.M.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="82" pageNumber="82" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="82" pageNumber="82">
Worker. Length 6 1/2 lines.-Exactly similar in form to 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:138734" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Drepanognathus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Drepanognathus cruentatus Smith" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="82" pageNumber="82" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cruentatus">cruentatus</taxonomicName>
, but with the head, thorax and abdomen black; the legs and mandibles pale rufo-testaceous, the femora and tibiae with dusky lines outside. Abdomen finely granulated and opake.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="82" pageNumber="82" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="82" pageNumber="82">Hab. Madras.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="82" pageNumber="82" type="discussion">
<paragraph lastPageNumber="83" pageId="82" pageNumber="82">
This species very closely resembles 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:138734" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Drepanognathus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Drepanognathus cruentatus Smith" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="82" pageNumber="82" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cruentatus">cruentatus</taxonomicName>
, but the joints of the antennae are much shorter, and the abdomen is granulated, the base being coarsely punctured. Whether either of the two species last described is the 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:186521" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Drepanognathus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Drepanognathus saltator (Jerdon)" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="82" pageNumber="82" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="saltator">saltator</taxonomicName>
of Jerdon it is impossible to determine satisfactorily; he says, &quot;abdomen very long; sting large; head and abdomen blackish-brown; thorax and legs rufous.&quot; The abdomen in both of the 
<taxonomicNameLabel pageId="82" pageNumber="82" rank="species">new species</taxonomicNameLabel>
is short.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
